The sum of an arithmetic series is equal to the average of the first and last term, multiplied by the number of terms, so the sum of the odd integers from 11 through 39 is \begin{align*}
11+13+15+\cdots+37+39 &= \frac{11+39}{2}\cdot\frac{39-11}{2}+20\\
&= 25\cdot 14 + 20 = \boxed{370}.
\end{align*}

We substitute $x=y^4$ into $x+y^2=1$ to get $y^4+y^2-1=0$.  Let $a=y^2$.  Then $a^2+a-1=0$.  The roots of this quadratic are $$a=\frac{-1\pm\sqrt5}{2}.$$If $a=y^2$, then $y=\pm\sqrt{\frac{-1\pm\sqrt5}{2}}$.  Hence the two intersections are at $(\pm\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}},\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}})$ and $(\pm\sqrt{\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}},\sqrt{\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}})$.  We choose the two points that are farthest apart, which are $(\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}},\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}})$ and $(-\sqrt{\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}},\sqrt{\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}})$.  The distance between these two points is \begin{align*}
&\sqrt{\left(\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}}+\sqrt{\frac{1+\sqrt5}{2}}\right)^2+\left(\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}}-\sqrt{\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}}\right)^2}\\
&=\sqrt{\frac{1+\sqrt5}{2}+\sqrt{\frac{-1+\sqrt5}{2}}+\frac{-1-\sqrt5}{2}}\\
&=\sqrt{\frac{1+\sqrt5}{2}}=\sqrt{\frac{3+\sqrt5}{4}}=\sqrt{\frac{(3+\sqrt5)^2}{16}}\\
&=\frac{3+\sqrt5}{4}=\boxed{\left(3,1\right)}.
